etymologies: Old English styrtan ‘to caper, leap’, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch storten ‘push’ and German stürzen ‘fall headlong, fling’. From the sense ‘sudden movement’ arose the sense ‘initiation of movement, setting out on a journey’ and hence ‘beginning of a process, etc.’

examples.text: the season starts in September
we ate before the show started

shortDefinitions: begin or be reckoned from particular point in time or space

synonyms.text: put one's shoulder to the wheel
